{"title_page": "FaceTime", "text_new": "{{About|the Apple product|other meanings|FaceTime (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n\nTo Brindley I missed you{{macOS sidebar}}\n\n'''FaceTime''' is a proprietary [[videotelephony]] product developed by [[Apple Inc.]] FaceTime is available on supported iOS mobile devices and Macintosh computers that run {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X Snow Leopard|Mac OS X 10.6.6]]}} and later. FaceTime supports any iOS device with a forward-facing camera and any [[Macintosh]] computer equipped with a FaceTime Camera. FaceTime Audio, an audio-only version, is available on any [[iDevice|iOS device]] that supports [[iOS 7]] or newer, and any Macintosh with a forward-facing camera running {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X Lion|Mac OS X 10.9.2]]}} and later. FaceTime is included for free in iOS and in macOS from {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X Lion]]}} (10.7) onwards.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/what-you-need-to-know-about-deleting-apple-apps-on-ios-10/|title=Deleting Apple apps on iOS 10? There's a catch.|newspaper=CNET|access-date=2016-12-08}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nApple bought the \"FaceTime\" name from FaceTime Communications, which changed its name to [[Actiance]] in January 2011.<ref name=\"FaceTime Communications\">{{cite web|url=http://facetime.com/LearnMore.aspx|title=Our name|work=Learn More|publisher=FaceTime Communications|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609083307/http://www.facetime.com/LearnMore.aspx|archive-date=June 9, 2010|url-status=dead|access-date=June 7, 2010|quote=Apple has announced that it will use 'FaceTime' as the trademark for its new video calling application. Our agreement with Apple to transfer the FaceTime trademark to them comes as we are rebranding our company to better reflect our capabilities. This is an Apple app that should come with your Apple product. We will be announcing a new name in the coming months.|df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmagazineuk.com/facetime-communications-confirms-its-change-of-name-to-actiance/article/561413/|title=FaceTime Communications confirms its change of name to Actiance|date=2011-01-25|work=SC Media UK|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref> On June 7, 2010, Apple CEO [[Steve Jobs]] announced FaceTime in conjunction with the [[iPhone 4]] in a [[stevenote|keynote speech]] at the [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference|2010 Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]]. Support for the fourth generation [[iPod Touch]] (the first model of iPod Touch equipped with cameras) was announced in conjunction with the device's release on September 8, 2010. FaceTime for {{nowrap|Mac OS X}} was announced on October 20, 2010.\n\nOn March 2, 2011, FaceTime support was announced for the newly introduced [[iPad 2]], which had forward- and rear-facing cameras.\n\nOn February 24, 2011, FaceTime left beta and was listed in the [[Mac App Store]] for [[United States dollar|US$]]0.99. Apple claims that it intended to provide the application free of charge, however, a provision of the [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act]] (2002) bars companies from providing an unadvertised new feature of an already-sold product without enduring \"onerous accounting measures\".<ref name=\"Macgasm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macgasm.net/2011/02/24/apple-charge-facetime|title=Apple charges for FaceTime|last=Macgasm|date=|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> {{As of|2017|12}}, the US$0.99 beta is still available for download from Apple.<ref name=\"softpedia FT beta\">{{cite web|url=http://mac.softpedia.com/get/Internet-Utilities/FaceTime.shtml|title=Mac|date=|publisher=Softpedia|at=link within last sentence \"The page provides access to FaceTime 0.9 Build 92 version\"|accessdate=}}</ref> FaceTime is included for free in macOS from {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X Lion]]}} (10.7) onwards and iOS.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[AT&T]] allowed customers to use FaceTime as long as they were [[tiered internet|tiered]], but blocked the application from working for customers with unlimited data plans. They were brought before the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) for [[net neutrality]] violations.<ref name=\"AT&T v. FaceTime\">{{cite web|url=http://transition.fcc.gov/cgb/oiac/Mobile-Broadband-FaceTime.pdf|title=AT&T/FaceTime Case Study|last=AT&T v. FaceTime}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, it was found that FaceTime would work seamlessly over 3G on all iPhone, iPad, and iPod Touch models that supported it. Even though FaceTime worked only over 3G at that time, it now supports 4G LTE calls on networks all over the world, availability being limited to operators' GSM plans.<ref name=\":1\">zaone [https://www.idevice.ro/2012/05/18/ios-5-1-1-ne-demonstreaza-ca-apple-va-permite-efectuarea-de-apeluri-facetime-prin-3g/ \"iOS 5.1.1 ne demonstreaza ca Apple va permite efectuarea de apeluri FaceTime prin 3G\"], \"iDevice.ro\", May 2011</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Apple announced that FaceTime would support group video and audio calls with up to 32 people in [[iOS 12]] and [[macOS Mojave]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/06/04/apple-facetime-group-chat-ios-12/|title=Apple's FaceTime offers group chats for up to 32 people|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\n {{Update|part= FaceTime group calling|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:IPhone calling screen.png|thumb|left|150px|The [[iPhone]]'s screen when a call is in progress, showing the FaceTime button (grayed out, middle of bottom row).]]\n\nFaceTime works by establishing a connection between two supported devices. Most Apple devices (such as iPhones, iPads and Macs) introduced after 2011 support FaceTime. FaceTime is currently incompatible with non-Apple devices or any other video calling services. Mac models introduced in 2011 have high-definition video FaceTime, which devices use automatically when both ends have a FaceTime HD camera.\n\nUnlike Mac OS X's [[iChat]], FaceTime currently does not support group conferencing but support has been announced for iOS 12. The application is a one-on-one video chat\u2014only two people can talk at once. If a second user calls and the user answers, the video chat with the previous user ends and a new video session begins with the second caller. In iPhone, if a phone call is pending and the user attempts to answer, the video call ends and the phone call begins with the next user.\n\nIncoming notifications on iOS devices are shown during a FaceTime call, but if they are opened, the video will be temporarily paused until the user is back in the FaceTime app. \n[[File:Paused FaceTime.png|thumbnail|left|Paused FaceTime Screen|219x219px]]\n\nOn the iPhone, a user can activate FaceTime during a phone call by pressing the FaceTime button or initiated FaceTime from their call history or the Contacts application. iOS 7 and newer also provide a separate FaceTime app, as there always has been on Apple's non-telephony devices: iPad, iPod Touch, and Mac.\n\nUntil the release of iOS 6, FaceTime required a WiFi connection to work. From iOS 6 onwards, FaceTime for the iPhone and iPad has supported FaceTime calls over cellular networks ([[3G]] or [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]) provided the carrier enabled it, which by mid-2013 virtually all carriers worldwide have allowed. FaceTime Audio uses about three [[megabyte]]s of data for every five minutes of conversation, with FaceTime Video using significantly more.<ref name=\"IW data usage 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iphonefaq.org/archives/974213|title=How much data does FaceTime audio calling use?|publisher=iPhoneFAQ|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref> Cellular talk time/minutes are not used after switching from a voice call to a FaceTime call.\n\nFaceTime calls can be placed from supported devices to any phone number or email address that is registered to the FaceTime service. A single email address can be registered to multiple devices and a call placed to that address rings all devices simultaneously.\n\n==Standards==\nThe FaceTime protocol is based on numerous open industry standards<ref name=\"AppleInsider standards 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/06/08/inside_iphone_4_facetime_video_calling.html|date=June 8, 2010|accessdate=June 9, 2010|title=Inside iPhone 4: FaceTime video calling|publisher=[[Apple community#AppleInsider|AppleInsider]]|author=Daniel Eran Dilger}}</ref> although it is not interoperable with other videotelephony systems:\n\n* [[H.264]] and [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]]-ELD \u2013 video and audio [[codec]]s respectively.\n* [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] \u2013 [[IETF]] signaling protocol for [[VoIP]].\n* [[Session Traversal Utilities for NAT|STUN]], [[Traversal Using Relay NAT|TURN]] and [[Interactive Connectivity Establishment|ICE]] \u2013 IETF technologies for traversing [[Firewall (computing)|firewalls]] and [[Network address translation|NAT]].\n* [[Real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]] and [[Secure Real-time Transport Protocol|SRTP]] \u2013 IETF standards for delivering real-time and encrypted media streams for VoIP.\n\nUpon the launch of the iPhone 4, Jobs stated that Apple would immediately start working with standards bodies to make the FaceTime protocol an \"open industry standard\". While the protocols are open standards, Apple's FaceTime service requires a client-side certificate.<ref name=\"Packetstan FT open standard 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.packetstan.com/2010/07/special-look-face-time-part-3-call.html|title=Special Look: Face Time (part 3: Call Connection Initialization)|publisher=Packetstan|first=Josh|last=Wright|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFaceTime calls are protected by [[end-to-end encryption]] so that only the sender and receiver can access them. Apple cannot decrypt this data.<!-- other reasoning could be political with other companies protecting their own marketplace interests. But not added, as no verifiable cite found! --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://images.apple.com/ipad/business/docs/iOS_Security_Feb14.pdf | title=iOS Security - iOS10 - March 2017 | publisher=Apple | date=March 2017 | accessdate=2017-09-02 }}</ref>\n\nCompared to most [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] implementations, Facetime adds techniques that enhance performance at the cost of breaking interoperability:<ref name=\"Apple's new Facetime - a SIP Perspective\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.krisk.org/2013/09/apples-new-facetime-sip-perspective.html |title=Apple's new Facetime - a SIP Perspective|publisher=Not Just AstLinux Stuff|first=Kristian|last=Kielhofner|date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 11, 2014}}</ref> port multiplexing, [[Session description protocol|SDP]] minimization and SDP compression.\n\n==FaceTime Audio==\nA new audio-only version of FaceTime, named FaceTime Audio, was announced during the annual [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]] (WWDC) keynote speech on June 10, 2013, and released with [[iOS 7]] on September 18, 2013. As an audio-only version of FaceTime, it effectively makes the protocol into a [[voice over IP|voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP), that competes with other mainstream providers in the field, including [[Skype]] ([[Microsoft]]).\n\nBased on the same [[AAC-LD]] audio protocol, the service provides high-quality audio. The iOS 7 betas limited FaceTime Audio to calls placed on a Wi-Fi network (the same original limitation of the video version of FaceTime), but the final release has removed that restriction to allow it to work over 3G and LTE data connections, as is the case with most carriers and plans with regard to FaceTime with video. Like the video version, FaceTime Audio is currently only available between Apple devices. The feature is not available to run on the [[iPod Touch]] 4th generation as the device does not support iOS 7 or later. FaceTime streaming over cellular data is unavailable for the [[iPhone 4]] and the [[iPad 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.apple.com/kb/HT4319|title=Use FaceTime with your iPhone, iPad, or iPod touch|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Limited availability==\n\n===By country===\n{{As of|2010|June|df=}}, FaceTime is not enabled on devices bought in the [[United Arab Emirates]] possibly due to regulations in this country that restrict IP-based communications. In addition, on devices bought in [[China]] only FaceTime Audio is disabled, while FaceTime Video is available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/facetime-audio-disabled-in-china/ |title=FaceTime audio disabled in China}}</ref> Devices bought outside these countries support both video and audio versions of FaceTime.<ref name=\"Register FT UAE SA limitations 1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/19/facetime |title=Apple wipes smile off FaceTime in the Middle East |newspaper=[[The Register]] |last=Ray |first=Bill |date=October 19, 2010 |accessdate=October 19, 2010}}</ref> Although [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], [[Qatar]] and [[Kuwait]] originally disabled FaceTime on the iPhone 4, they later re-enabled the feature through a carrier update for existing phone owners, and made it pre-enabled on any newly purchased iPhone. In March 2018, FaceTime is available for iPhones in [[Saudi Arabia]] upon updating to iOS 11.3. In August 2019, FaceTime is available for iPhones in [[Pakistan]] upon updating to iOS 12.4.\n\n===By iOS version===\nAs of April 16, 2014, FaceTime ceased working on earlier versions of iOS which had previously supported it (iOS 4, 5 & 6). This was because the client-side certificate used to authenticate a genuine Apple device with FaceTime servers (amongst other uses<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chasechristian.com/blog/2014/04/ios-client-certificate-expiration-april-16-2014/ |publisher=Chase Christian Blog|date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=February 24, 2016|title=iOS Client Certificate Expiration - April 16, 2014}}</ref>) expired on that date. Apple chose not to release an update to this certificate for all devices for which a newer major iOS version (with a new, valid certificate) was available. Apple did release a minor update, to the certificate only, for all [[OS X]] versions which could run FaceTime, and also for earlier versions of iOS, but only for the small number of devices which could run FaceTime but which could not run a newer major version of iOS (4th generation iPod touch). The result of this policy was that almost all iOS users had to update the iOS version on their devices if they wished to continue using FaceTime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techrepublic.com/article/ios-6-users-no-longer-able-to-use-facetime-ios-7-upgrade-required/ |publisher=[[TechRepublic]] |date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=February 24, 2016|title=iOS 6 users no longer able to use FaceTime, iOS 7 upgrade required}}</ref> (This limitation applied even to users of [[iOS jailbreaking|jailbroken]] devices since, even with a legally jailbroken device, it would have been not only difficult but also illegal{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} to extract and install Apple's new certificate, without Apple's permission, in order to work around this issue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/jailbreak/comments/240ovk/can_we_fix_facetime_on_devices_staying_on_ios6_by/ |publisher=Reddit |date=April 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |title=Can we fix Facetime on devices staying on iOS6 by backporting the new certificates from 6.0.6/7.1.1?}}</ref> {{unreliablesource |date=May 2017}}<!--This is a Reddit discussion so clearly is not a reliable source. Further, it does not even clearly conclude it's illegal which makes sense since complicated things like this may not be illegal in all jurisdictions whatever Apple may want-->)\n\n=== On Android and Windows ===\nDue to the proprietary nature of FaceTime, it is currently unavailable on other platforms including Android<ref>{{cite web |url=https://joyofandroid.com/facetime-for-android/ |publisher=John|date=October 17, 2018 |title=Facetime on Android}}</ref> and Windows.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ifacetimeapp.com |publisher=Kevin|date=January 26, 2019 |title=Facetime App}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n=== Group FaceTime Bug ===\nOn January 28, 2019, a bug was discovered in the FaceTime app that allowed users to [[eavesdrop]] on other users without their knowledge through an exploit.<ref name=\"SMHBug\">{{cite news |last1=Biggs |first1=Tim |title=FaceTime bug lets you eavesdrop on your iPhone contacts |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/facetime-bug-lets-you-eavesdrop-on-your-iphone-contacts-20190129-p50uam.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> It was later discovered the video feed could be enabled without the other users' acceptance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2019/01/28/facetime-bug-hear-audio/|title=Major iPhone FaceTime bug lets you hear the audio of the person you are calling \u2026 before they pick up|last=Mayo|first=Benjamin|date=2019-01-28|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Apple said in a statement that it would release a fix for the exploit shortly, disabling Group FaceTime for the time being.<ref name=\"CNNBug\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Heather |title=iPhone FaceTime bug lets you eavesdrop on other people |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/28/tech/apple-face-time-bug/index.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |work=CNN |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> The bug was named \"FacePalm\" by security researchers,<ref>{{cite news |last=Perlroth |first=Nicole |title=Apple Was Slow to Act on FaceTime Bug That Allows Spying on iPhones |date=January 29, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/technology/facetime-glitch-apple.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019}}</ref> and affects iOS devices running Facetime on iOS 12.1 or Macintosh computers running MacOS 10.14.1 Mojave. On February 7, Apple fixed the FaceTime vulnerabilities in iOS 12.1.4 and a Supplemental Update for macOS Mojave 10.14.3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Joshua |title=Everything You Need To Know About the FaceTime Spying Bug |url=https://www.intego.com/mac-security-blog/facetime-spying-bug-discovered-temporarily-worked-around/ |website=The Mac Security Blog |publisher=Intego Security |accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the bug gained international attention on January 28, 2019, the bug was found by a 14-year old high school student in Arizona. He and his mother tried for more than a week to warn Apple about the problem through Facebook and Twitter after discovering the bug on January 20. However the pair found it impossible to reach anyone at the company. \"Short of smoke signals, I was trying every method that someone could use to get a hold of someone at Apple,\" said Ms. Thompson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/teenager-and-his-mom-tried-to-warn-apple-of-facetime-bug-11548783393|title=Teenager and His Mom Tried to Warn Apple of FaceTime Bug|last=McMillan|first=Robert|date=2019-01-29|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>  On January 25, 2019, they posted a video to [[YouTube]] demonstrating the bug.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gGQx8tx-78w|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> As news of the bug finally gained media coverage, Ms Thompson wrote: \"I have letters, emails, tweets and msgs. sent to Apple for 10+ days reporting the Group FaceTime bug that lets someone listen in. My teenager discovered it! Never heard back from them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-47050433|title=Mother and son 'tried to warn Apple of bug'|last=Lee|first=Dave|date=2019-01-29|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.apple.com/mac/facetime/}}\n\n{{Apple}}\n{{iOS}}\n{{macOS}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facetime}}\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n[[Category:Assistive technology]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:2010 software]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2010]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the Apple product|other meanings|FaceTime (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = FaceTime\n| title = FaceTime\n| logo = FaceTime (macOS).svg\n| logo size = 150px\n| screenshot = <!-- Deleted image deleted: [[File:FaceTime Mac iOS.png|300px]] -->\n| caption = A FaceTime call from a [[Macintosh|Mac]] (''left'') and an [[iPhone 5S]] (''right'').\n| developer = Apple Inc.\n| released = {{Plainlist |\n* '''iOS''': {{Start date and age|2010|06|24}}\n* '''Mac''': {{Start date and age|2011|02|24}}\n}}\n| discontinued = \n| latest release version = {{Plainlist |\n* '''iOS''': 13.3\n* '''Mac''': 10.15.2\n}}\n| latest release date = {{Plainlist |\n* '''iOS''': {{Start date and age|2019|12|10}}\n* '''Mac''': {{Start date and age|2019|12|10}}\n}}\n| latest preview version = \n| latest preview date = <!-- {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| programming language = \n| operating system = {{Plainlist |\n* '''iOS''': [[iOS 4|4]] and later\n* '''Mac''': [[Mac OS X Snow Leopard|Mac&nbsp;OS&nbsp;X 10.6.6]] and later\n}}\n| platform = {{Flatlist |\n* [[iPhone]]\n* [[Apple Watch]]\n* [[iPad]]\n* [[iPad Air]]\n* [[iPad Pro]]\n* [[iPad Mini]]\n* [[iPod Touch]]\n* [[Macintosh|Mac]]\n}}\n| size = {{Plainlist |\n* '''iOS''': 686.1&nbsp;[[Kilobyte|KB]]\n* '''Mac''': 8.8&nbsp;[[Megabyte|MB]]\n}}\n| language = {{Flatlist |\n* English\n* Arabic\n* Catalan\n* Croatian\n* Czech\n* Danish\n* Dutch\n* Finnish\n* French\n* German\n* Greek\n* Hebrew\n* Hindi\n* Hungarian\n* Indonesian\n* Italian\n* Japanese\n* Korean\n* Malay\n* Norwegian Bokm\u00e5l\n* Polish\n* Portuguese\n* Romanian\n* Russian\n* Simplified Chinese\n* Slovak\n* Spanish\n* Swedish\n* Thai\n* Traditional Chinese\n* Turkish\n* Ukrainian\n* Vietnamese\n}}\n| genre = {{Plainlist |\n* '''Both''': [[Social networking service|Social 