ies. This is an Apple app that should come with your Apple product. We will be announcing a new name in the coming months.|df=mdy}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.scmagazineuk.com/facetime-communications-confirms-its-change-of-name-to-actiance/article/561413/|title=FaceTime Communications confirms its change of name to Actiance|date=2011-01-25|work=SC Media UK|access-date=2018-06-22|language=en}}</ref> On June 7, 2010, Apple CEO [[Steve Jobs]] announced FaceTime in conjunction with the [[iPhone 4]] in a [[stevenote|keynote speech]] at the [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference|2010 Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]]. Support for the fourth generation [[iPod Touch]] (the first model of iPod Touch equipped with cameras) was announced in conjunction with the device's release on September 8, 2010. FaceTime for {{nowrap|Mac OS X}} was announced on October 20, 2010.\n\nOn March 2, 2011, FaceTime support was announced for the newly introduced [[iPad 2]], which had forward- and rear-facing cameras.\n\nOn February 24, 2011, FaceTime left beta and was listed in the [[Mac App Store]] for [[United States dollar|US$]]0.99. Apple claims that it intended to provide the application free of charge, however, a provision of the [[Sarbanes\u2013Oxley Act]] (2002) bars companies from providing an unadvertised new feature of an already-sold product without enduring \"onerous accounting measures\".<ref name=\"Macgasm\">{{cite web|url=http://www.macgasm.net/2011/02/24/apple-charge-facetime|title=Apple charges for FaceTime|last=Macgasm|date=|accessdate=February 24, 2011}}</ref> {{As of|2017|12}}, the US$0.99 beta is still available for download from Apple.<ref name=\"softpedia FT beta\">{{cite web|url=http://mac.softpedia.com/get/Internet-Utilities/FaceTime.shtml|title=Mac|date=|publisher=Softpedia|at=link within last sentence \"The page provides access to FaceTime 0.9 Build 92 version\"|accessdate=}}</ref> FaceTime is included for free in macOS from {{nowrap|[[Mac OS X Lion]]}} (10.7) onwards and iOS.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n[[AT&T]] allowed customers to use FaceTime as long as they were [[tiered internet|tiered]], but blocked the application from working for customers with unlimited data plans. They were brought before the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) for [[net neutrality]] violations.<ref name=\"AT&T v. FaceTime\">{{cite web|url=http://transition.fcc.gov/cgb/oiac/Mobile-Broadband-FaceTime.pdf|title=AT&T/FaceTime Case Study|last=AT&T v. FaceTime}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2011, it was found that FaceTime would work seamlessly over 3G on all iPhone, iPad, and iPod Touch models that supported it. Even though FaceTime worked only over 3G at that time, it now supports 4G LTE calls on networks all over the world, availability being limited to operators' GSM plans.<ref name=\":1\">zaone [https://www.idevice.ro/2012/05/18/ios-5-1-1-ne-demonstreaza-ca-apple-va-permite-efectuarea-de-apeluri-facetime-prin-3g/ \"iOS 5.1.1 ne demonstreaza ca Apple va permite efectuarea de apeluri FaceTime prin 3G\"], \"iDevice.ro\", May 2011</ref>\n\nIn June 2018, Apple announced that FaceTime would support group video and audio calls with up to 32 people in [[iOS 12]] and [[macOS Mojave]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2018/06/04/apple-facetime-group-chat-ios-12/|title=Apple's FaceTime offers group chats for up to 32 people|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-06-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Implementation==\n {{Update|part= FaceTime group calling|date=October 2019}}\n[[File:IPhone calling screen.png|thumb|left|150px|The [[iPhone]]'s screen when a call is in progress, showing the FaceTime button (grayed out, middle of bottom row).]]\n\nFaceTime works by establishing a connection between two supported devices. Most Apple devices (such as iPhones, iPads and Macs) introduced after 2011 support FaceTime. FaceTime is currently incompatible with non-Apple devices or any other video calling services. Mac models introduced in 2011 have high-definition video FaceTime, which devices use automatically when both ends have a FaceTime HD camera.\n\nUnlike Mac OS X's [[iChat]], FaceTime currently does not support group conferencing but support has been announced for iOS 12. The application is a one-on-one video chat\u2014only two people can talk at once. If a second user calls and the user answers, the video chat with the previous user ends and a new video session begins with the second caller. In iPhone, if a phone call is pending and the user attempts to answer, the video call ends and the phone call begins with the next user.\n\nIncoming notifications on iOS devices are shown during a FaceTime call, but if they are opened, the video will be temporarily paused until the user is back in the FaceTime app. \n[[File:Paused FaceTime.png|thumbnail|left|Paused FaceTime Screen|219x219px]]\n\nOn the iPhone, a user can activate FaceTime during a phone call by pressing the FaceTime button or initiated FaceTime from their call history or the Contacts application. iOS 7 and newer also provide a separate FaceTime app, as there always has been on Apple's non-telephony devices: iPad, iPod Touch, and Mac.\n\nUntil the release of iOS 6, FaceTime required a WiFi connection to work. From iOS 6 onwards, FaceTime for the iPhone and iPad has supported FaceTime calls over cellular networks ([[3G]] or [[LTE (telecommunication)|LTE]]) provided the carrier enabled it, which by mid-2013 virtually all carriers worldwide have allowed. FaceTime Audio uses about three [[megabyte]]s of data for every five minutes of conversation, with FaceTime Video using significantly more.<ref name=\"IW data usage 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iphonefaq.org/archives/974213|title=How much data does FaceTime audio calling use?|publisher=iPhoneFAQ|accessdate=July 7, 2016}}</ref> Cellular talk time/minutes are not used after switching from a voice call to a FaceTime call.\n\nFaceTime calls can be placed from supported devices to any phone number or email address that is registered to the FaceTime service. A single email address can be registered to multiple devices and a call placed to that address rings all devices simultaneously.\n\n==Standards==\nThe FaceTime protocol is based on numerous open industry standards<ref name=\"AppleInsider standards 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/10/06/08/inside_iphone_4_facetime_video_calling.html|date=June 8, 2010|accessdate=June 9, 2010|title=Inside iPhone 4: FaceTime video calling|publisher=[[Apple community#AppleInsider|AppleInsider]]|author=Daniel Eran Dilger}}</ref> although it is not interoperable with other videotelephony systems:\n\n* [[H.264]] and [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]]-ELD \u2013 video and audio [[codec]]s respectively.\n* [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] \u2013 [[IETF]] signaling protocol for [[VoIP]].\n* [[Session Traversal Utilities for NAT|STUN]], [[Traversal Using Relay NAT|TURN]] and [[Interactive Connectivity Establishment|ICE]] \u2013 IETF technologies for traversing [[Firewall (computing)|firewalls]] and [[Network address translation|NAT]].\n* [[Real-time Transport Protocol|RTP]] and [[Secure Real-time Transport Protocol|SRTP]] \u2013 IETF standards for delivering real-time and encrypted media streams for VoIP.\n\nUpon the launch of the iPhone 4, Jobs stated that Apple would immediately start working with standards bodies to make the FaceTime protocol an \"open industry standard\". While the protocols are open standards, Apple's FaceTime service requires a client-side certificate.<ref name=\"Packetstan FT open standard 1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.packetstan.com/2010/07/special-look-face-time-part-3-call.html|title=Special Look: Face Time (part 3: Call Connection Initialization)|publisher=Packetstan|first=Josh|last=Wright|date=July 9, 2010|accessdate=March 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFaceTime calls are protected by [[end-to-end encryption]] so that only the sender and receiver can access them. Apple cannot decrypt this data.<!-- other reasoning could be political with other companies protecting their own marketplace interests. But not added, as no verifiable cite found! --><ref>{{cite web | url=https://images.apple.com/ipad/business/docs/iOS_Security_Feb14.pdf | title=iOS Security - iOS10 - March 2017 | publisher=Apple | date=March 2017 | accessdate=2017-09-02 }}</ref>\n\nCompared to most [[Session Initiation Protocol|SIP]] implementations, Facetime adds techniques that enhance performance at the cost of breaking interoperability:<ref name=\"Apple's new Facetime - a SIP Perspective\">{{cite web|url=http://blog.krisk.org/2013/09/apples-new-facetime-sip-perspective.html |title=Apple's new Facetime - a SIP Perspective|publisher=Not Just AstLinux Stuff|first=Kristian|last=Kielhofner|date=September 20, 2013 |accessdate=September 11, 2014}}</ref> port multiplexing, [[Session description protocol|SDP]] minimization and SDP compression.\n\n==FaceTime Audio==\nA new audio-only version of FaceTime, named FaceTime Audio, was announced during the annual [[Apple Worldwide Developers Conference]] (WWDC) keynote speech on June 10, 2013, and released with [[iOS 7]] on September 18, 2013. As an audio-only version of FaceTime, it effectively makes the protocol into a [[voice over IP|voice over Internet Protocol]] (VoIP), that competes with other mainstream providers in the field, including [[Skype]] ([[Microsoft]]).\n\nBased on the same [[AAC-LD]] audio protocol, the service provides high-quality audio. The iOS 7 betas limited FaceTime Audio to calls placed on a Wi-Fi network (the same original limitation of the video version of FaceTime), but the final release has removed that restriction to allow it to work over 3G and LTE data connections, as is the case with most carriers and plans with regard to FaceTime with video. Like the video version, FaceTime Audio is currently only available between Apple devices. The feature is not available to run on the [[iPod Touch]] 4th generation as the device does not support iOS 7 or later. FaceTime streaming over cellular data is unavailable for the [[iPhone 4]] and the [[iPad 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://support.apple.com/kb/HT4319|title=Use FaceTime with your iPhone, iPad, or iPod touch|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Limited availability==\n\n===By country===\n{{As of|2010|June|df=}}, FaceTime is not enabled on devices bought in the [[United Arab Emirates]] possibly due to regulations in this country that restrict IP-based communications. In addition, on devices bought in [[China]] only FaceTime Audio is disabled, while FaceTime Video is available.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/facetime-audio-disabled-in-china/ |title=FaceTime audio disabled in China}}</ref> Devices bought outside these countries support both video and audio versions of FaceTime.<ref name=\"Register FT UAE SA limitations 1\">{{cite news |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/19/facetime |title=Apple wipes smile off FaceTime in the Middle East |newspaper=[[The Register]] |last=Ray |first=Bill |date=October 19, 2010 |accessdate=October 19, 2010}}</ref> Although [[Egypt]], [[Jordan]], [[Qatar]] and [[Kuwait]] originally disabled FaceTime on the iPhone 4, they later re-enabled the feature through a carrier update for existing phone owners, and made it pre-enabled on any newly purchased iPhone. In March 2018, FaceTime is available for iPhones in [[Saudi Arabia]] upon updating to iOS 11.3. In August 2019, FaceTime is available for iPhones in [[Pakistan]] upon updating to iOS 12.4.\n\n===By iOS version===\nAs of April 16, 2014, FaceTime ceased working on earlier versions of iOS which had previously supported it (iOS 4, 5 & 6). This was because the client-side certificate used to authenticate a genuine Apple device with FaceTime servers (amongst other uses<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chasechristian.com/blog/2014/04/ios-client-certificate-expiration-april-16-2014/ |publisher=Chase Christian Blog|date=April 21, 2014 |accessdate=February 24, 2016|title=iOS Client Certificate Expiration - April 16, 2014}}</ref>) expired on that date. Apple chose not to release an update to this certificate for all devices for which a newer major iOS version (with a new, valid certificate) was available. Apple did release a minor update, to the certificate only, for all [[OS X]] versions which could run FaceTime, and also for earlier versions of iOS, but only for the small number of devices which could run FaceTime but which could not run a newer major version of iOS (4th generation iPod touch). The result of this policy was that almost all iOS users had to update the iOS version on their devices if they wished to continue using FaceTime.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techrepublic.com/article/ios-6-users-no-longer-able-to-use-facetime-ios-7-upgrade-required/ |publisher=[[TechRepublic]] |date=April 29, 2014|accessdate=February 24, 2016|title=iOS 6 users no longer able to use FaceTime, iOS 7 upgrade required}}</ref> (This limitation applied even to users of [[iOS jailbreaking|jailbroken]] devices since, even with a legally jailbroken device, it would have been not only difficult but also illegal{{citation needed|date=May 2017}} to extract and install Apple's new certificate, without Apple's permission, in order to work around this issue.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/jailbreak/comments/240ovk/can_we_fix_facetime_on_devices_staying_on_ios6_by/ |publisher=Reddit |date=April 26, 2014 |accessdate=February 24, 2016 |title=Can we fix Facetime on devices staying on iOS6 by backporting the new certificates from 6.0.6/7.1.1?}}</ref> {{unreliablesource |date=May 2017}}<!--This is a Reddit discussion so clearly is not a reliable source. Further, it does not even clearly conclude it's illegal which makes sense since complicated things like this may not be illegal in all jurisdictions whatever Apple may want-->)\n\n=== On Android and Windows ===\nDue to the proprietary nature of FaceTime, it is currently unavailable on other platforms including Android<ref>{{cite web |url=https://joyofandroid.com/facetime-for-android/ |publisher=John|date=October 17, 2018 |title=Facetime on Android}}</ref> and Windows.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://ifacetimeapp.com |publisher=Kevin|date=January 26, 2019 |title=Facetime App}}</ref>\n\n== Controversy ==\n=== Group FaceTime Bug ===\nOn January 28, 2019, a bug was discovered in the FaceTime app that allowed users to [[eavesdrop]] on other users without their knowledge through an exploit.<ref name=\"SMHBug\">{{cite news |last1=Biggs |first1=Tim |title=FaceTime bug lets you eavesdrop on your iPhone contacts |url=https://www.smh.com.au/technology/facetime-bug-lets-you-eavesdrop-on-your-iphone-contacts-20190129-p50uam.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> It was later discovered the video feed could be enabled without the other users' acceptance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://9to5mac.com/2019/01/28/facetime-bug-hear-audio/|title=Major iPhone FaceTime bug lets you hear the audio of the person you are calling \u2026 before they pick up|last=Mayo|first=Benjamin|date=2019-01-28|website=9to5Mac|language=en-US|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> Apple said in a statement that it would release a fix for the exploit shortly, disabling Group FaceTime for the time being.<ref name=\"CNNBug\">{{cite news |last1=Kelly |first1=Heather |title=iPhone FaceTime bug lets you eavesdrop on other people |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2019/01/28/tech/apple-face-time-bug/index.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019 |work=CNN |date=January 29, 2019}}</ref> The bug was named \"FacePalm\" by security researchers,<ref>{{cite news |last=Perlroth |first=Nicole |title=Apple Was Slow to Act on FaceTime Bug That Allows Spying on iPhones |date=January 29, 2019 |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/29/technology/facetime-glitch-apple.html |accessdate=January 29, 2019}}</ref> and affects iOS devices running Facetime on iOS 12.1 or Macintosh computers running MacOS 10.14.1 Mojave. On February 7, Apple fixed the FaceTime vulnerabilities in iOS 12.1.4 and a Supplemental Update for macOS Mojave 10.14.3.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Long |first1=Joshua |title=Everything You Need To Know About the FaceTime Spying Bug |url=https://www.intego.com/mac-security-blog/facetime-spying-bug-discovered-temporarily-worked-around/ |website=The Mac Security Blog |publisher=Intego Security |accessdate=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the bug gained international attention on January 28, 2019, the bug was found by a 14-year old high school student in Arizona. He and his mother tried for more than a week to warn Apple about the problem through Facebook and Twitter after discovering the bug on January 20. However the pair found it impossible to reach anyone at the company. \"Short of smoke signals, I was trying every method that someone could use to get a hold of someone at Apple,\" said Ms. Thompson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/teenager-and-his-mom-tried-to-warn-apple-of-facetime-bug-11548783393|title=Teenager and His Mom Tried to Warn Apple of FaceTime Bug|last=McMillan|first=Robert|date=2019-01-29|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>  On January 25, 2019, they posted a video to [[YouTube]] demonstrating the bug.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gGQx8tx-78w|title=YouTube|website=www.youtube.com|access-date=2019-01-31}}</ref> As news of the bug finally gained media coverage, Ms Thompson wrote: \"I have letters, emails, tweets and msgs. sent to Apple for 10+ days reporting the Group FaceTime bug that lets someone listen in. My teenager discovered it! Never heard back from them.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-47050433|title=Mother and son 'tried to warn Apple of bug'|last=Lee|first=Dave|date=2019-01-29|access-date=2019-01-31|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website|https://www.apple.com/mac/facetime/}}\n\n{{Apple}}\n{{iOS}}\n{{macOS}}\n{{Instant messaging}}\n{{Telecommunications}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Facetime}}\n[[Category:Videotelephony]]\n[[Category:Assistive technology]]\n[[Category:IOS]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:2010 software]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2010]]\n", "name_user": "109.149.56.6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Facebook is Grubb)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FaceTime"}
{"title_page": "Siobhan McDonald", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = S\u00edobhan McDonald\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[New York City]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| residence        = [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n| known_for        = Crystalline: Hidden Monuments\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com}}\n| module           = \n}}\n \n'''S\u00edobhan McDonald''' is an [[Irish people|Irish]] artist based in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]] known for her recent artwork is centered around climate change.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSiobhan McDonald was in [[New York City|New York]] of [[Northern Ireland]] parents from [[County Monaghan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Cathy |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald: the art of scientific exploration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-the-art-of-scientific-exploration-1.2147180 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> but was raised in [[Ireland]] as her family moved back to [[Monaghan]], Ireland when she was two. As a child, McDonald was fascinated by geology and collected rocks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahlstrom |first1=Dick |title=Layer by layer: how Siobh\u00e1n McDonald paints like a geologist |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/layer-by-layer-how-siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-paints-like-a-geologist-1.1820753 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald holds a Bachelor's degree in Art and Design from [[Ulster University]] and [[Master of Fine Arts|Masters in Visual Arts Practices]] from [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=O\u2019Sullivan |first1=John |title=Her crystalline mine |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/her-crystalline-mine-b5nrgfp8c |work=[[The Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Visual Artists \u2013 Design {{!}} Previous Residents {{!}} Artists in Residence |url=https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/en/residencies/artistes-en-residence/previous-residents?c=16 |publisher=[[Irish College in Paris]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=TEDxUCD {{!}} TED |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/22942 |website=www.ted.com}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMcDonald is the artist in residence in the School of Natural Sciences at Trinity College Dublin.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last1=Leach |first1=Crist\u00edn |title=Artist Siobhan McDonald on geology, time and the Anthropocene |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2019/0129/1026276-artist-siobhan-mcdonald-on-geology-time-and-the-anthropocene/ |publisher=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |language=en |date=5 February 2019}}</ref> She had several shows and often uses various materials like Gold, Cooper and Charcoal to paint on paper, board and canvas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Artist, Fine Art Prices, Auction Records for Siobh\u00e1n McDonald |url=https://www.askart.com/artist/Siobhan_McDonald/11177710/Siobhan_McDonald.aspx |website=www.askart.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Her work influenced by her interest in the natural world as she experimented with using a mixed palette of plaster, pigments, beeswax as well as traditional oil paints to create works that have a deep connection to nature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, McDonald undertook an expedition to the Arctic circle which was a pivotal point in her career moving to create larger installations and more imaginative and varied pieces of sculpture and video alongside her paintings. She collaborates on an ongoing basis with scientists and geologists as part of her work, bridging the gap between art and science.<ref>{{cite news |title=My Arctic Voyage of Self Discovery |url=https://thegloss.ie/arctic-role/ |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=5 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrington |first1=Damian |title=The Anthropocene epoch: scientists declare dawn of human-influenced age |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/aug/29/declare-anthropocene-epoch-experts-urge-geological-congress-human-impact-earth |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\nIn 2019, McDonald traveled on another expedition to Catania with three scientists from TCD to study Mount Etna\u2019s pulsing, volatile terrain in the hope to discover the volcano\u2019s chemical make-up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rainsford |first1=Sue |title=Ash to art: Can Mount Etna\u2019s eruptions tackle carbon emissions? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/ash-to-art-can-mount-etna-s-eruptions-tackle-carbon-emissions-1.3760154 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\nIn December 2019, McDonald\u2019s work was exhibited in the \"Datami\" exhibition in BOZAR, [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Datami |url=https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/160618-datami |website=[[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald\u2019s work was exhibited in Ireland and internationally and known in many private collections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eye of the Storm \u2013 exhibition by Siobhan McDonald \u2013 DIAS |url=https://www.dias.ie/2012/04/30/eye-of-the-storm-exhibition-by-siobhan-mcdonald/ |publisher=[[Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies]]}}</ref>\nHer most recent work, Hidden Monuments was exhibited in the [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]] from February to March 2019.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Art |first1=Limerick City Gallery of |title=Siobhan McDonald, Crystalline: Hidden Monuments |url=http://gallery.limerick.ie/LCGAExhibitions/LCGAExhibitionsArchive/2019Exhibitions/SiobhanMcDonaldCrystallineHiddenMonuments.html |website=limerick.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Crystalline: Hidden Monuments {{!}} Siobhan McDonald at Limerick City Gallery of Art |url=https://visualartists.ie/events/crystalline-hidden-monuments-siobhan-mcdonald-at-limerick-city-gallery-of-art/ |publisher=[[Visual Artists Ireland]] |date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Her practice in recent times has been focused on art intersecting with science on the theme of climate change.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breathe the pressure |url=https://www.businesspost.ie/more-life-arts/breathe-the-pressure-2710c8f9 |work=[[Business Post]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobhan McDonald\u2019s chance encounters with a changing world |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/siobhan-mcdonalds-chance-encounters-changing-world/ |publisher=[[Apollo (magazine)]] |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald was chosen to be the artist-in-residence for Climate Whirl arts program at the University of Helsinki in 2020.  She was the selected as the sole artist from 168 applications by a jury composed by [[:fi:Jaana_B\u00e4ck|Jaana B\u00e4ck]], professor in Forest-Atmosphere Interactions (INAR, University of Helsinki), [[:fi:Timo Vesala|Timo Vesala]], professor in Meteorology (INAR, University of Helsinki), Henna Paunu, chief curator at EMMA (Espoo Museum for Modern Art), Paula Toppila executive director at IHME Helsinki and Ulla Taipale, curator of Climate Whirl.<ref>http://climatewhirl.fi/en/news Climate Whirl artist-in-residence 2020 is selected </ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n* 2020 - Artist in Residence, Climate Whirl arts program, 2020, University of Helsinki<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2017 \u2013 The Trinity Creative Award, [[Trinity College Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trinity Creative - FUTURE BREATH |url=https://www.tcd.ie/trinity-creative/challenge/2017/siobhan-mc-donald.php |publisher=[[Trinity College Dublin]]}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Bursary|Bursary Award]] by Arts Council Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=webmaster |first1=Arts Council |title=Who we funded |url=http://www.artscouncil.ie/funding-decisions/?&Fund=Bursary%20award&Year=2017 |publisher=[[Arts Council (Ireland)]] |date=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Residency at [[Centre Culturel Irlandais]], Paris.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2016  \u2013 BAI Sound and Vision, [[RT\u00c9 lyric fm|RT\u00c9 Lyric FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyric Feature Preview: An artist in the Arctic Circle |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2016/1005/821628-lyric-feature-preview/ |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |language=en |date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n* Culture Ireland Award: Imagining Ireland in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=When Plants Remember - Crystalline |url=https://www.cultureireland.ie/GB18/event/when-plants-remember-crystalline |publisher=[[Culture Ireland]]}}</ref>\n\n== Solo Exhibitions ==\n*''Monuments for the future'', [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]], Ireland.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*''When plants remember'', The Henry Fox Talbot Museum, UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art at Lacock |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/lacock-abbey-fox-talbot-museum-and-village/lists/art-and-installations-at-lacock-abbey |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', [[Highlanes Gallery]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlanes Gallery - Siobhan McDonald \u2013 A Change in the Signal \u2013 Crystalline, until Nov 25th |url=http://www.highlanes.ie/Activity.aspx?ActivityID=3330 |website=www.highlanes.ie}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', Centre Culturel Irlandais, Paris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casassus |first1=Barbara |title=Arctic expeditions and stars collide to create 'quietly powerful' show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2017/mar/17/crystalline-doomed-arctic-expeditions-and-stars-collide-to-create-quietly-powerful-show |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n*''Eye of the Storm'', The Galway Arts Centre.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Courtney |first1=Kevin |title=Volcanic art: \u2018Iceland is like a blank canvas\u2019 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/volcanic-art-iceland-is-like-a-blank-canvas-1.1508369 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Disappearing Worlds''''',''' [[Taylor Galleries]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorgalleries.ie/Siobhan-McDonald-Crystalline-Disappearing-Worlds|title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Crystalline: Disappearing Worlds - Taylor Galleries|website=www.taylorgalleries.ie|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com/ Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Alumni of the Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:Irish artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = S\u00edobhan McDonald\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| birth_name       = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date       = \n| birth_place      = [[New York City]]\n| death_date       = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> \n| death_place      = \n| resting_place    = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} -->\n| nationality      = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| residence        = [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]]\n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = [[Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n| known_for        = Crystalline: Hidden Monuments\n| notable_works    = \n| style            = \n| home_town        = \n| movement         = \n| spouse           = \n| partner          = \n| awards           = <!-- {{awd|award|year|title|role|name}} (optional) -->\n| elected          = \n| patrons          = \n| memorials        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com}}\n| module           = \n}}\n \n'''S\u00edobhan McDonald''' is an [[Irish people|Irish]] artist based in [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]] known for her recent artwork is centered around climate change.\n\n== Early life and education ==\nSiobhan McDonald was in [[New York City|New York]] of [[Northern Ireland]] parents from [[County Monaghan]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dillon |first1=Cathy |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald: the art of scientific exploration |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/art-and-design/siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-the-art-of-scientific-exploration-1.2147180 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> but was raised in [[Ireland]] as her family moved back to [[Monaghan]], Ireland when she was two. As a child, McDonald was fascinated by geology and collected rocks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ahlstrom |first1=Dick |title=Layer by layer: how Siobh\u00e1n McDonald paints like a geologist |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/layer-by-layer-how-siobh%C3%A1n-mcdonald-paints-like-a-geologist-1.1820753 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald holds a Bachelor's degree in Art and Design from [[Ulster University]] and [[Master of Fine Arts|Masters in Visual Arts Practices]] from [[D\u00fan Laoghaire Institute of Art, Design and Technology]] in 2011.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last1=O\u2019Sullivan |first1=John |title=Her crystalline mine |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/her-crystalline-mine-b5nrgfp8c |work=[[The Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Visual Artists \u2013 Design {{!}} Previous Residents {{!}} Artists in Residence |url=https://www.centreculturelirlandais.com/en/residencies/artistes-en-residence/previous-residents?c=16 |publisher=[[Irish College in Paris]]}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=TEDxUCD {{!}} TED |url=https://www.ted.com/tedx/events/22942 |website=www.ted.com}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMcDonald is the artist in residence in the School of Natural Sciences at Trinity College Dublin.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |last1=Leach |first1=Crist\u00edn |title=Artist Siobhan McDonald on geology, time and the Anthropocene |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2019/0129/1026276-artist-siobhan-mcdonald-on-geology-time-and-the-anthropocene/ |publisher=[[RT\u00c9.ie]] |language=en |date=5 February 2019}}</ref> She had several shows and often uses various materials like Gold, Cooper and Charcoal to paint on paper, board and canvas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Artist, Fine Art Prices, Auction Records for Siobh\u00e1n McDonald |url=https://www.askart.com/artist/Siobhan_McDonald/11177710/Siobhan_McDonald.aspx |website=www.askart.com}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Her work influenced by her interest in the natural world as she experimented with using a mixed palette of plaster, pigments, beeswax as well as traditional oil paints to create works that have a deep connection to nature.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2015, McDonald undertook an expedition to the Arctic circle which was a pivotal point in her career moving to create larger installations and more imaginative and varied pieces of sculpture and video alongside her paintings. She collaborates on an ongoing basis with scientists and geologists as part of her work, bridging the gap between art and science.<ref>{{cite news |title=My Arctic Voyage of Self Discovery |url=https://thegloss.ie/arctic-role/ |work=The Gloss Magazine |date=5 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Carrington |first1=Damian |title=The Anthropocene epoch: scientists declare dawn of human-influenced age |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2016/aug/29/declare-anthropocene-epoch-experts-urge-geological-congress-human-impact-earth |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=29 August 2016}}</ref>\nIn 2019, McDonald traveled on another expedition to Catania with three scientists from TCD to study Mount Etna\u2019s pulsing, volatile terrain in the hope to discover the volcano\u2019s chemical make-up.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rainsford |first1=Sue |title=Ash to art: Can Mount Etna\u2019s eruptions tackle carbon emissions? |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/ash-to-art-can-mount-etna-s-eruptions-tackle-carbon-emissions-1.3760154 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\nIn December 2019, McDonald\u2019s work was exhibited in the \"Datami\" exhibition in BOZAR, [[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=McDonald |first1=Siobhan |title=Science meets art as Solar Orbiter embarks on its journey to the sun |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/science-meets-art-as-solar-orbiter-embarks-on-its-journey-to-the-sun-1.4195267 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Datami |url=https://www.bozar.be/en/activities/160618-datami |website=[[Centre for Fine Arts, Brussels]] |language=en}}</ref> McDonald\u2019s work was exhibited in Ireland and internationally and known in many private collections.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eye of the Storm \u2013 exhibition by Siobhan McDonald \u2013 DIAS |url=https://www.dias.ie/2012/04/30/eye-of-the-storm-exhibition-by-siobhan-mcdonald/ |publisher=[[Dublin Institute for Advanced Studies]]}}</ref>\nHer most recent work, Hidden Monuments was exhibited in the [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]] from February to March 2019.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web |last1=Art |first1=Limerick City Gallery of |title=Siobhan McDonald, Crystalline: Hidden Monuments url=http://gallery.limerick.ie/LCGAExhibitions/LCGAExhibitionsArchive/2019Exhibitions/SiobhanMcDonaldCrystallineHiddenMonuments.html |website=limerick.ie |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Crystalline: Hidden Monuments {{!}} Siobhan McDonald at Limerick City Gallery of Art |url=https://visualartists.ie/events/crystalline-hidden-monuments-siobhan-mcdonald-at-limerick-city-gallery-of-art/ |publisher=[[Visual Artists Ireland]] |date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Her practice in recent times has been focused on art intersecting with science on the theme of climate change.<ref>{{cite news |title=Breathe the pressure |url=https://www.businesspost.ie/more-life-arts/breathe-the-pressure-2710c8f9 |work=[[Business Post]] |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Siobhan McDonald\u2019s chance encounters with a changing world |url=https://www.apollo-magazine.com/siobhan-mcdonalds-chance-encounters-changing-world/ |publisher=[[Apollo (magazine)]] |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald was chosen to be the artist-in-residence for Climate Whirl arts program at the University of Helsinki in 2020.  She was the selected as the sole artist from 168 applications by a jury composed by [[:fi:Jaana_B\u00e4ck|Jaana B\u00e4ck]], professor in Forest-Atmosphere Interactions (INAR, University of Helsinki), [[:fi:Timo Vesala|Timo Vesala]], professor in Meteorology (INAR, University of Helsinki), Henna Paunu, chief curator at EMMA (Espoo Museum for Modern Art), Paula Toppila executive director at IHME Helsinki and Ulla Taipale, curator of Climate Whirl.<ref>http://climatewhirl.fi/en/news Climate Whirl artist-in-residence 2020 is selected </ref>\n\n== Awards and accolades ==\n* 2020 - Artist in Residence, Climate Whirl arts program, 2020, University of Helsinki<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2017 \u2013 The Trinity Creative Award, [[Trinity College Dublin]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Trinity Creative - FUTURE BREATH |url=https://www.tcd.ie/trinity-creative/challenge/2017/siobhan-mc-donald.php |publisher=[[Trinity College Dublin]]}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 [[Bursary|Bursary Award]] by Arts Council Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |last1=webmaster |first1=Arts Council |title=Who we funded |url=http://www.artscouncil.ie/funding-decisions/?&Fund=Bursary%20award&Year=2017 |publisher=[[Arts Council (Ireland)]] |date=14 February 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Residency at [[Centre Culturel Irlandais]], Paris.<ref name=\":2\" />\n* 2016  \u2013 BAI Sound and Vision, [[RT\u00c9 lyric fm|RT\u00c9 Lyric FM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lyric Feature Preview: An artist in the Arctic Circle |url=https://www.rte.ie/culture/2016/1005/821628-lyric-feature-preview/ |publisher=[[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] |language=en |date=5 October 2016}}</ref>\n* Culture Ireland Award: Imagining Ireland in the UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=When Plants Remember - Crystalline |url=https://www.cultureireland.ie/GB18/event/when-plants-remember-crystalline |publisher=[[Culture Ireland]]}}</ref>\n\n== Solo Exhibitions ==\n*''Monuments for the future'', [[Limerick City Gallery of Art]], Ireland.<ref name=\":3\" />\n*''When plants remember'', The Henry Fox Talbot Museum, UK.<ref>{{cite web |title=Art at Lacock |url=https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/lacock-abbey-fox-talbot-museum-and-village/lists/art-and-installations-at-lacock-abbey |publisher=[[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', [[Highlanes Gallery]], Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |title=Highlanes Gallery - Siobhan McDonald \u2013 A Change in the Signal \u2013 Crystalline, until Nov 25th |url=http://www.highlanes.ie/Activity.aspx?ActivityID=3330 |website=www.highlanes.ie}}</ref>\n*''Crystalline'', Centre Culturel Irlandais, Paris.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casassus |first1=Barbara |title=Arctic expeditions and stars collide to create 'quietly powerful' show |url=https://www.theguardian.com/science/blog/2017/mar/17/crystalline-doomed-arctic-expeditions-and-stars-collide-to-create-quietly-powerful-show |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=17 March 2017}}</ref>\n*''Eye of the Storm'', The Galway Arts Centre.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Courtney |first1=Kevin |title=Volcanic art: \u2018Iceland is like a blank canvas\u2019 |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/science/volcanic-art-iceland-is-like-a-blank-canvas-1.1508369 |work=[[The Irish Times]] |language=en}}</ref>\n*''Disappearing Worlds''''',''' [[Taylor Galleries]], Dublin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.taylorgalleries.ie/Siobhan-McDonald-Crystalline-Disappearing-Worlds|title=Siobh\u00e1n McDonald - Crystalline: Disappearing Worlds - Taylor Galleries|website=www.taylorgalleries.ie|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.siobhanmcdonald.com/ Official Website]\n\n[[Category:Alumni of the Limerick School of Art and Design]]\n[[Category:Irish artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:Add missing pipe", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siobhan_McDonald"}
{"title_page": "Fatty acid methyl ester", "text_new": "'''Fatty acid methyl esters''' ('''FAME''') are a type of [[fatty acid ester]] that are derived by [[transesterification]] of [[fat]]s with [[methanol]].  The molecules in [[biodiesel]] are primarily FAMEs, usually obtained from [[vegetable oil]]s by transesterification. They are used to produce detergents and biodiesel.<ref name=\"Ullmann\">{{cite book|title=Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry|last=Anneken|first=David J.|last2=Both|first2=Sabine|last3=Christoph|first3=Ralf|last4=Fieg|first4=Georg|last5=Steinberner|first5=Udo|last6=Westfechtel|first6=Alfred|publisher=Wiley-VCH|year=2006|isbn=9783527306732|location=Weinheim|pages=|chapter=Fatty Acids|doi=10.1002/14356007.a10_245.pub2|oclc=910197915}}</ref> FAMES are typically produced by an [[alkali]]-catalyzed reaction between fats and methanol in the presence of base such as sodium hydroxide, [[sodium methoxide]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vyas|first=Amish P.|last2=Verma|first2=Jaswant L.|last3=Subrahmanyam|first3=N.|date=2010|title=A review on FAME production processes|journal=Fuel|volume=89|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1016/j.fuel.2009.08.014|issn=0016-2361}}</ref> or potassium hydroxide. One of the reasons for FAME use in biodiesel instead of free fatty acids is to nullify any corrosion that free fatty acids would cause to the metals of engines, production facilities and so forth. Free fatty acids are only mildly acidic, but in time can cause cumulative corrosion unlike their esters. As an improved quality, FAMEs also usually have about 12-15 units higher [[cetane number]] than their unesterified counterparts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/chemistry-of-fossil-fuels-and-biofuels/55F8E62F729DF25CE4D40109440860DA|title=Chemistry of Fossil Fuels and Biofuels|last=Schobert|first=Harold H.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2013|isbn=9780511844188|location=Cambridge, NY|pages=62\u201364|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511844188|oclc=823724682}}</ref>\n\n:[[Image:Transesterification FAME.svg|center]]\n\n==Other details==\nEvery [[microorganism]] has its specific FAME profile ([[microbial fingerprinting]]). After [[triglyceride]]s, [[fatty acid]]s and certain other [[lipid]]s of some cultured microbes are esterified, they become volatile enough for analysis with [[gas chromatography]] which is used to create FAME profile.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sekora|first=Nicholas S.|last2=Lawrence|first2=Kathy S.|last3=Agudelo|first3=Paula|last4=van Santen|first4=Edzard|last5=McInroy|first5=John A.|date=2009|title=Using FAME Analysis to Compare, Differentiate, and Identify Multiple Nematode Species |journal=Journal of Nematology|volume=41|issue=3|pages=163\u2013173 |pmc=3380492|pmid=22736811}}</ref> These profiles can be used as a tool for [[microbial source tracking]] (MST) to identify pathological bacteria strains<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Duran|first=Metin|last2=Haznedaro\u011flu|first2=Berat Z.|last3=Zitomer|first3=Daniel H.|title=Microbial source tracking using host specific FAME profiles of fecal coliforms|journal=Water Research|volume=40|issue=1|pages=67\u201374|doi=10.1016/j.watres.2005.10.019|pmid=16360192|year=2006}}</ref> and for characterizing new species of bacteria.\n\nFor example, a profile created from [[Microbiological culture|cultured bacteria]] from some water sample can be compared to a profile of known pathological bacteria to find out if the water is polluted by feces or not.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biodiesel production]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fatty Acid Methyl Ester}}\n[[Category:Fatty acid esters]]\n[[Category:Biodiesel]]\n[[Category:Methyl esters]]\n", "text_old": "'''Fatty acid methyl esters''' ('''FAME''') are a type of [[fatty acid ester]] that are derived by [[transesterification]] of [[fat]]s with [[methanol]].  The molecules in [[biodiesel]] are primarily FAMEs, usually obtained from [[vegetable oil]]s by transesterification. They are used to produce detergents and biodiesel.<ref name=\"Ullmann\">{{cite book|title=Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry|last=Anneken|first=David J.|last2=Both|first2=Sabine|last3=Christoph|first3=Ralf|last4=Fieg|first4=Georg|last5=Steinberner|first5=Udo|last6=Westfechtel|first6=Alfred|publisher=Wiley-VCH|year=2006|isbn=9783527306732|location=Weinheim|pages=|chapter=Fatty Acids|doi=10.1002/14356007.a10_245.pub2|oclc=910197915}}</ref> FAMES are typically produced by an [[alkali]]-catalyzed reaction between fats and methanol in the presence of base such as sodium hydroxide, [[sodium methoxide]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vyas|first=Amish P.|last2=Verma|first2=Jaswant L.|last3=Subrahmanyam|first3=N.|date=2010|title=A review on FAME production processes|journal=Fuel|volume=89|issue=1|pages=1\u20139|doi=10.1016/j.fuel.2009.08.014|issn=0016-2361}}</ref> or potassium hydroxide. One of the reasons for FAME use in biodiesel instead of free fatty acids is to nullify any corrosion that free fatty acids would cause to the metals of engines, production facilities and so forth. Free fatty acids are only mildly acidic, but in time can cause cumulative corrosion unlike their esters. As an improved quality, FAMEs also usually have about 12-15 units higher [[cetane number]] than their unesterified counterparts.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/chemistry-of-fossil-fuels-and-biofuels/55F8E62F729DF25CE4D40109440860DA|title=Chemistry of Fossil Fuels and Biofuels|last=Schobert|first=Harold H.|publisher=Cambridge University Press|year=2013|isbn=9780511844188|location=Cambridge, NY|pages=62\u201364|doi=10.1017/CBO9780511844188|oclc=823724682}}</ref>\n\n:[[Image:Transesterification FAME.svg|center]]\n\n==Other details==\nEvery [[microorganism]] has its specific FAME profile ([[microbial fingerprinting]]). After [[triglyceride]]s, [[fatty acid]]s and certain other [[lipid]]s of some cultured microbes are esterified, they become volatile enough for analysis with [[gas chromatography]] which is used to create FAME profile.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sekora|first=Nicholas S.|last2=Lawrence|first2=Kathy S.|last3=Agudelo|first3=Paula|last4=van Santen|first4=Edzard|last5=McInroy|first5=John A.|date=2009|title=Using FAME Analysis to Compare, Differentiate, and Identify Multiple Nematode Species |journal=Journal of Nematology|volume=41|issue=3|pages=163\u2013173 |pmc=3380492|pmid=22736811}}</ref> These profiles can be used as a tool for [[microbial source tracking]] (MST) to identify pathological bacteria strains<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Duran|first=Metin|last2=Haznedaro\u011flu|first2=Berat Z.|last3=Zitomer|first3=Daniel H.|title=Microbial source tracking using host specific FAME profiles of fecal coliforms|journal=Water Research|volume=40|issue=1|pages=67\u201374|doi=10.1016/j.watres.2005.10.019|pmid=16360192|year=2006}}</ref> and for characterizing new species of bacteria.\n\nFor example, a profile created from [[Microbiological culture|cultured bacteria]] from some water sample be can be compared to a profile of known pathological bacteria to find out if the water is polluted by feces or not.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Biodiesel production]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fatty Acid Methyl Ester}}\n[[Category:Fatty acid esters]]\n[[Category:Biodiesel]]\n[[Category:Methyl esters]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther details:Typo fixing, replaced: be can be  \u2192  can be", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fatty_acid_methyl_ester"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nevada", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing pandemic in Nevada, United States}}\n{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name =2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nevada\n| width =\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| virus_strain =[[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| location =[[Nevada]], U.S.\n| first_case = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], U.S.\n| arrival_date = March 5, 2020\n| origin =\n| confirmed_cases = 1,113\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases = 10\n| deaths = 26\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|http://dpbh.nv.gov/coronavirus/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]''' was confirmed to have reached the U.S. state of [[Nevada]] on March 5, 2020. As of March 31, 2020, 1,113 positive cases and 26 deaths were reported in the state.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Seeman |first1=Matthew |title=First death tied to coronavirus reported in Nevada, 35 cases in Clark County |url=https://news3lv.com/news/local/first-death-tied-to-coronavirus-reported-in-clark-county-case-number-up-to-35 |website=KSNV |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Nevada medical cases chart}}\nOn March 5, 2020, Nevada reported the first case of [[COVID-19]].  The patient, a man in his 50s, recently traveled to [[Washington (state)|Washington]] state and lives in [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Farber |first1=Madeline |title=Nevada reports first coronavirus case in patient who recently traveled to Washington state |url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/nevada-reports-first-coronavirus-case |website=Fox News |accessdate=March 17, 2020 |date=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, 2020, Nevada reported its first death from the coronavirus: a man in his 60s, from Las Vegas.<ref>{{cite web |title=Nevada Reports 1st Death From New Coronavirus in Vegas Area |url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/nevada/articles/2020-03-16/nevada-reports-1st-death-from-new-coronavirus-in-vegas-area |newspaper=USA Today |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, 2020, Governor [[Steve Sisolak]] ordered all non-essential businesses closed for 30 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/business/casinos-gaming/nevada-casinos-closing-for-30-days-following-state-order-1984236/|title=Nevada casinos closing for 30 days following state order|last=Velotta|first=Richard N.|last2=Schulz|first2=Bailey|date=2020-03-18|website=Las Vegas Review-Journal|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2020, Governor [[Steve Sisolak]] prohibited stockpiling of the anti-malarial drugs [[chloroquine]] and [[hydroxychloroquine|hydroxychloroquine (Plaquenil)]].<ref>[https://www.reviewjournal.com/local/local-nevada/sisolak-signs-restriction-order-for-2-drugs-1990149/ Sisolak signs restriction order for 2 drugs] By Bill Dentzer, Las Vegas Review-Journal, 24 March 2020</ref>\n\n==Impact on sports==\n{{Main|Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on sports}}\nOn March 12, the [[National Hockey League]], the season was suspended for an indefinite amount of time, affecting the [[2019\u201320 Vegas Golden Knights season|Vegas Golden Knights]].<ref name=nhl>[https://www.nhl.com/news/nhl-coronavirus-status/c-316155530 NHL statement on coronavirus] NHL, March 12, 2020</ref>\n\nIn college sports, the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association]] cancelled all winter and spring tournaments, most notably the [[NCAA Division I|Division I]] [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|men]]'s and [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|women]]'s basketball tournaments, affecting colleges and universities statewide.<ref name=ncaa>[https://www.ncaa.org/about/resources/media-center/news/ncaa-cancels-remaining-winter-and-spring-championships NCAA cancels remaining winter and spring championships] NCAA, March 12, 2020</ref> On March 16, the [[National Junior College Athletic Association]] also canceled the remainder of the winter seasons as well as the spring seasons.<ref>[https://www.mlive.com/sports/2020/03/njcaa-cancels-spring-sports-basketball-nationals-amid-coronavirus-outbreak.html NJCAA cancels spring sports, basketball nationals amid coronavirus outbreak] MLive.com, March 16, 2020</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States]]\n* [[U.S. state and local government response to 2020 coronavirus pandemic]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://dpbh.nv.gov/coronavirus/ Coronavirus information] from the [[Nevada Department of Health and Human Services]]\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Medicine|United States|Viruses|Coronavirus disease 2019|Pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Nevada]]\n[[Category:2020 in Nevada|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Nevada]]\n[[Category:Health in Nevada]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{Current event|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name =2020 coronavirus pandemic in Nevada\n| width =\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| image_upright =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| map1 =\n| legend1 =\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| map4 =\n| legend4 =\n| map5 =\n| legend5 =\n| virus_strain =[[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| location =[[Nevada]], U.S.\n| first_case = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]], U.S.\n| arrival_date = March 5, 2020\n| origin =\n| confirmed_cases = 1,113\n| suspected_cases =\n| severe_cases =\n| recovery_cases = 10\n| deaths = 26\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|http://dpbh.nv.gov/coronaviru